The standard .NET approach is to use the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package. It wraps all `System.IO` statics behind injectable interfaces.

**1. Install it:**
```bash
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers  # for tests
```

**2. Inject `IFileSystem` instead of using statics:**
```csharp
public class ConfigService
{
    private readonly IFileSystem _fs;

    public ConfigService(IFileSystem fs) => _fs = fs;

    public string Load(string path) => _fs.File.ReadAllText(path);
    public void Save(string path, string data) => _fs.File.WriteAllText(path, data);
    public bool HasDir(string path) => _fs.Directory.Exists(path);
}
```

**3. Test with `MockFileSystem`:**
```csharp
var fs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/config.json", new MockFileData("{\"key\":\"value\"}") }
});

var svc = new ConfigService(fs);
Assert.Equal("{\"key\":\"value\"}", svc.Load("/config.json"));
```

**4. Register in DI for production:**
```csharp
services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

This avoids rolling your own wrapper — `IFileSystem` covers `File`, `Directory`, `Path`, `DriveInfo`, etc. out of the box.
